properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: The Special Weather Statement has been upgraded to a Wind Warning for Iqaluit. A strong winter storm will move from the Labrador Sea into the Davis Strait tonight, bringing snow and strong winds to much of southern and eastern Baffin Island. This system will produce wind gusts of 80 to 90 km/h through many communities tonight into Tuesday. These strong winds may combine with snow to produce near-blizzard conditions at times. Snowfall amounts will remain low for most communities, however moderate to heavy snow is possible along portions of the eastern coast. This snow may end up bringing higher snowfall accumulations to Clyde River and Qikiqtarjuaq. The winds and snow will diminish on Tuesday night. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NUstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NUStorm.

properties.Title: Winter Storm Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Hazardous winter conditions are expected. A disturbance tracking across the northern Prairies and its associated warm front will bring mixed precipitation to the Lynn Lake, Leaf Rapids and Pukatawagan areas. The warm front, which straddles the area from northwest to southeast, will be the dividing line between wet snow and rain. Northeast of the front heavy snowfall is expected with snowfall totals of 10 to 15 cm possible by Tuesday morning. Meanwhile, near the front, the precipitation will gradually change over to freezing rain or rain. The main precipitation area is forecast to exit the region by Tuesday morning but some lingering patchy fog, drizzle or freezing drizzle maybe in the area until midday. ### Visibility may be suddenly reduced at times in heavy snow. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to MBstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #MBStorm.

properties.Summary:
Description: Snowfall with total amounts of 10 to 15 cm is expected. A low pressure system moving across the northern Prairies will bring heavy snowfall to northern Manitoba tonight.
